content.title: Effective Parenting is to take daily efforts to connect with children on a meaningful and personal level.
How to discipline child without yelling?
content.textLine1:
1. Establish Clear Rules
2. Discuss negatives beforehand
3. Provide positive reinforcement
4. Offer warnings when appropriate and follow through with consequences
5. Praise your child for good behavior

Remember: Children learn by watching what parents do

content.title: How does a parent reward a child?
content.textLine1:
1. Plan a trip to a park.
2. Pick a movie for the weekend
3. Allow them to decide dinner menu
4. A family activity
5. 30 mins of extra screen time

content.title: How to punish children for bad behavior
content.textLine1:
1. Do not hit them
2. Do not yell or shout at them
3. Rather turn the punishment into problem solving
4. Give them tasks to finish the bad behavior
5. Cut short the perks(eg: 30 mins less screen time)

content.title: How to discipline a toddler?
content.textLine1:
1. Avoid stressful situations
2. You must think like a toddler
3. Practice the art of distraction
4. Give the child a break
5. Stay Calm
6. Know when to give in
7. Be consistent

content.title: Lastly, try to be an authoritative parent
content.textLine2:
Allow autonomy and encourage independence
Reason with children instead of demanding blind obedience
Set clear limit on behavior

content.question: Sclera

tasks.title: Endocrine System
tasks.instructions: The endocrine system is the collection of glands that produce hormones that regulate metabolism, growth and development, tissue function, sexual function, reproduction, sleep, and mood, among other things

content.question: Ovaries
content.hintAudio: Ovaries are two endocrine glands in a female’s lower abdomen; Responsible for egg production and estrogen and progesterone secretion

content.question: Pancreas
content.hintAudio: Pancreas is the Endocrine gland behind the stomach.Islet cells secrete hormones from the pancreas

content.question: Testes
content.hintAudio: Testes are two endocrine glands enclosed in the scrotal sac of a male; responsible for sperm production and testosterone secretion

content.question: Adrenaline
content.hintAudio: Produced by the adrenal medulla; also called epinephrine Adrenaline increases neart rate and blood pressure

content.question: Aldosterone
content.hintAudio: Aldosterone is produced by the adrenal cortex; increases salt reabsorption

content.question: Androgen
content.hintAudio: Male hormone produced by the testes and to a lesser extent by the adrenal cortex; testosterone is an example

content.question: Calcitonin
content.hintAudio: Produced by the thyroid gland. Calcitonin lowers blood calcium. Also called thyrocalcitonin

content.question: Cortisol
content.hintAudio: Cortisol is produced by the adrenal cortex; increases blood sugar

content.question: Epinephrine
content.hintAudio: Epinephrine produced by the adrenal medulla; also called adrenaline. epinephrine increases heart rate and blood pressure and dilates airways

content.question: Estrogen
content.hintAudio: Estrogen is female hormone produced by the ovaries and to a lesser extent b y the adrenal cortex

content.question: Glucagon
content.hintAudio: Glucagon is a hormone produced by the islet cells of the pancreas; increases Blood sugar by conversion of glycogen to glucose

content.question: Insulin
content.hintAudio: Insulin lowers blood sugar by transport and Conversion of glucose to glycogen

content.question: Norepinephrine
content.hintAudio: Norepinephrine increases heart rate and blood pressure

content.question: Oxytocin
content.hintAudio: Oxytocin stimulates contraction of the uterus during labor and child birth

content.question: Progesterone
content.hintAudio: Produced by the ovaries.Progesterone prepares the uterus for pregnancy

content.question: Somatotropin
content.hintAudio: Produced by the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland; also called growth hormone.

content.question: Testosterone
content.hintAudio: Male hormone produced by the testes

content.question: Thyroxine
content.hintAudio: Produced by the thyroid gland; Thyroxine increases metabolism in cells.

content.question: Triiadithyronine
content.hintAudio: Triiadithyronine increases metabolism in cells

content.question: Vasopressin
content.hintAudio: Vasopressin is secreted by the posterior lobe of the pituitary gland; also called antidiuretic hormone.

content.question: Catecholamines
content.hintAudio: Hormones derived from an amino acid and secreted by the adrenal medulla. Epinephrine is a catecholamine

content.question: Corticosteroids
content.hintAudio: Corticosteroids are hormones produced by the adrenal cortex. Glucocorticoids and mineralocorticoids are examples.

content.question: Electrolyte
content.hintAudio: A mineral salt found in the blood and tissues and necessary for Proper functioning of cells; potassium, sodium and calcium are examples.

content.question: Glucocorticoid
content.hintAudio: Necessary for use of sugars, fats and proteins by the body and for the body’s normal response to stress

content.question: Homeostasis
content.hintAudio: Homeostasis is the tendency of an organism to maintain a constant internal environment.

content.question: Hormone
content.hintAudio: Hormone is a substance that is produced by an endocrine gland and that travels through the blood to a distant organ or gland where it gland

content.question: Hypothalamus
content.hintAudio: Hypothalamus is a region of the brain that lies below the thalamus and above the pituitary gland. It produces releasing factors that stimulate the pituitary gland to release hormones

content.question: Mineralocorticoid
content.hintAudio: Mineralocorticoid is a steroid hormone produced by the adrenal cortex to regulate the mineral salts (electrolytes) and water balance in the body. aldosterone is an example

content.question: Sympathomimetic
content.hintAudio: Pertaining to mimicking or copying the effect of the Sympathetic nervous system. Adrenaline is a sympathomimetic hormone

content.question: Palliative
content.hintAudio: Palliative means relieving symptoms, but not curing

content.question: Radionuclide

content.question: Scan
content.hintAudio: A scan is a general term for images of organ parts

content.question: Scintiscanner
content.hintAudio: Scintiscanner is a machine used to detect radiopharmaceuticals in the body for diagnostic imaging

content.question: Tagging
content.hintAudio: Attaching a radionuclide to a chemical and following its course in the body

content.question: Ultrasound
content.hintAudio: An ultrasound is a diagnostic technique that projects and retrieves high-frequency sound waves as they echo off of parts of the body

content.question: Uptake
content.hintAudio: Uptake is the rate of absorption of a radionuclide into an organ or tissue
